le brings together diverse issues and statistics—the plight of single mothers; the time crunch faced by many parents; the problem of housework; patterns of work, employment and marriage; and much more—in a rich and engaging analysis that draws from history, economics, political science, sociology, government documents, and census data to put gender at the center of the social and economic changes of the past decades. With its broad historical and theoretical sweep, clear charts and tables, and accessible writing, From Marriage to the Market will be an essential resource for understanding the tumultuous changes currently transforming American society.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aWomenxEconomic conditionsxUnited States. 0aWomenxEmploymentxHistoryx20th centuryxUnited States. 0aWomenxEmploymentzUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aWomenxSocial conditionsxUnited States. 0aWomenzUnited StatesxEconomic conditions. 0aWomenzUnited StatesxSocial conditions. 0aWork and familyxUnited StatesxUnited States. 0aWork and familyzUnited States. 4aLabor & Industrial Relations. 4aPolitical Science. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Labor & Industrial Relations.2bisacsh1 aThistle, Susan, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z97831106904220 cprintz978052024646140uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052093919640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520939196423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520939196/original  a978-3-11-069042-2  University of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles